# RIG Mesh

A top-level orchestrator CLI for the RIG Sovereign system — `boot`, `audit`,
`probe`, `recover`, `status`. Treats every daemon, service, and library as a
declarative **Subsystem** with three probe kinds (HTTP / heartbeat / launchd),
a topological dependency graph, and a uniform verb dispatcher.

Built on Python stdlib only. Optional FastAPI dashboard at `:8091`.

```
                 ┌──────────────────┐
                 │   rig-mesh CLI   │
                 └────────┬─────────┘
                          │ verbs: status / list / probe / audit / boot / recover
                ┌─────────▼──────────┐
                │   CommandRouter    │
                └─────────┬──────────┘
                ┌─────────▼──────────┐
                │     RigMaster      │
                └─────────┬──────────┘
       ┌──────────────────┼──────────────────┐
┌──────▼──────┐    ┌──────▼──────┐    ┌──────▼──────┐
│ Subsystem   │    │ Audit       │    │ Boot        │
│ Registry    │    │ Runner      │    │ Runner      │
└─────────────┘    └─────────────┘    └─────────────┘
```

## Install

From source:
```bash
git clone https://github.com/rodgemd1-lgtm/RIG-Mesh.git
cd RIG-Mesh
pip install -e .                    # CLI only
pip install -e ".[dashboard]"       # CLI + :8091 FastAPI dashboard
pip install -e ".[dev]"             # everything + tests
```

Once installed, the `rig-mesh` console script is on your `$PATH`.

## Quickstart

```bash
# Version
rig-mesh version

# Probe one subsystem
rig-mesh probe --name proof-store

# Snapshot every subsystem's current health
rig-mesh status

# Run a full audit + write JSON + bind a proof if proof_system is reachable
rig-mesh audit

# Cold-boot every subsystem in topological order
rig-mesh boot --max-wait-s 10

# Run recovery flows (restart dead daemons + replay blocked queue by default)
rig-mesh recover --dry-run
rig-mesh recover                 # actually applies
rig-mesh recover --flows restart_dead_daemons,replay_blocked_queue
```

All output is JSON; exit code reflects health (`0` ok / `1` warn or fail).

## Verbs

| Verb | What it does |
|---|---|
| `status` | Probe every subsystem, return JSON snapshot with aggregate verdict |
| `list` | Print every registered subsystem with its declared probes + deps |
| `probe --name X` | Run a single subsystem's health probe |
| `audit` | Full audit with artifact write to `<state>/rig-master/audit-*.json` + best-effort proof binding |
| `boot [--max-wait-s N]` | Cold-boot in topological dependency order; aborts on critical failure |
| `recover [--flows ...] [--dry-run]` | Run recovery flows: `restart_dead_daemons`, `replay_blocked_queue`, `restore_proof_store_from_backup` |
| `version` | Print rig_mesh version |

## Configuration

The CLI auto-detects the RIG Sovereign repo root by walking up from its own
install path looking for a `CLAUDE.md` marker. Override with env vars:

```bash
export RIG_REPO_ROOT=/path/to/your/Startup-Intelligence-OS
export RIG_STATE_DIR=/custom/state/dir
```

For the dashboard, optional auth bypass for local TestClient probes:

```bash
export RIG_TEST_BYPASS_AUTH=1     # production NEVER sets this
```

## Dashboard (optional)

```bash
pip install -e ".[dashboard]"
python -m uvicorn rig_mesh.dashboard:app --host 127.0.0.1 --port 8091
open http://127.0.0.1:8091/
```

Six endpoints:
- `GET /health` — liveness (always 200)
- `GET /` — HTML status page, auto-refreshes every 10s
- `GET /api/status` — JSON snapshot
- `GET /api/list` — subsystem registry
- `GET /api/probe/{name}` — single probe
- `POST /api/audit` / `POST /api/boot` / `POST /api/recover` — mutating

## Subsystem registry

17 canonical subsystems registered out-of-the-box, including:

```
proof-store           library  critical
idle-queue            daemon   critical  depends_on=[proof-store]
cell-watcher          daemon
healer-daemon         daemon
rig-247-supervisor    daemon            depends_on=[proof-store, idle-queue]
monitor-runner        daemon            depends_on=[proof-store]
meta-monitor          daemon            depends_on=[monitor-runner]
cockpit-v5            service           depends_on=[proof-store]
deviation-dashboard   service
studio-dashboard      service
progress-board        service
avis-nps              service
litellm-mesh-router   service
backup-runner         daemon
retention-runner      daemon
escalation-runner     daemon
node-worker           daemon
```

Each declares the most authoritative probe available (HTTP > heartbeat >
launchd) and its topological dependencies.

## Testing

```bash
pip install -e ".[test]"
pytest
```

61 tests covering registry, probes, audit aggregation, boot ordering with
critical-fail abort, recovery flows, router dispatch, CLI argparse, and the
FastAPI dashboard (auth-bypass aware).

## Design notes

- **stdlib only for the core**. HTTP probes use raw `socket` — no `requests`
  dep. FastAPI is opt-in via the `dashboard` extra.
- **No live LLM**. Every check is deterministic. The optional proof-binding
  reaches into a `proof_system` module if installed; otherwise degrades.
- **Truth-tracker doctrine**. Probes always report what's actually reachable
  right now, not what a YAML claims. The CLI's exit code reflects live state.
- **macOS-first**. `launchctl bootstrap` / `kickstart` for daemon control.
  Heartbeat and HTTP probes work on any platform.

